  <section> <!--10-->
    <title>Afghan Poppyland</title>
    <abstract>
      Afghanistan is the source of the vast mojrity ‒ around 90% ‒ of the world's illicit opiates. A global network of routes facilitated by international crime groups ensures that heroin is trafficked from production countries in South West Asia to global consumer markets. Multiple factors affect traffickers’ choice of routes including risk of detection, geo-political changes, logistical difficulties, topographic considerations and existing relationships between criminal groups. The so-called Balkan route is possibly the most important heroin trafficking route of all.
    </abstract>
    <chapter>
      <title>The Balkan Route</title>
      <paragraph>Three broad trafficking routes have been identified for the movement of Afghan heroin. The “northern route” is the main heroin trafficking corridor linking Afghanistan to Central Asia and the large market of the Russian Federation. An emerging network of trajectories known collectively as the “southern route” travels southward from Afghanistan, either through Pakistan or the Islamic Republic of Iran, crosses the Indian Ocean and targets Africa, Europe, and Asia. The third and oldest route is an overland trajectory that crosses the Islamic Republic of Iran, Turkey and South-Eastern Europe to Western and Central Europe and is colloquially known as the “Balkan route”.</paragraph>
      <paragraph>Turkey is the main transit countries for illicit opiates bound for the final destination markets in Europe, although some of those markets also receive illicit opiates via the southern route and the northern route, or directly from Pakistan.</paragraph>
      <paragraph>Here are the most important receiving Europe countries:</paragraph>
