  <section> <!--13-->
    <title>The Drug Production Chain</title>
    <chapter>
      <paragraph>
        <list type="unordered">
          <item>FARMERS. For the hill tribe people of Southeast Asia opium is used as a currency, and it is sold or traded for basic necessities like food, clothing, and utensils. Opium is also used locally as a substitute for modern medicines.</item>
          <item>REFINERY. Most of the opium produced in Afghanistan is brought to Pakistan, where there are many laboratories for the refining of heroin. From here the product comes back to Afghanistan or it’s moved directly to the Balkan Route through Iran.</item>
          <item>COURIER. In the last decades drug smugglers have been forced to be more creative because trafficking laws are getting more stringent. Couriers usually swallow bags of heroin, cross the border, and wait for the bags to run their digestive course.</item>
          <item>CRIMINAL ORG. Drug trafficking continues to be the most lucrative form of business for criminal organizations, with an estimated annual value of more than $300 billion.</item>
          <item>DEALERS. Drugs handled by organized crime are then divided between various chains of dealers. To maximize individual profit, different substances are often added at each stop, making the product less pure and even more dangerous.</item>
          <item>BUYERS. It is estimated that a total of 246 million people, or 1 out of 20 people between the ages of 15 and 64 years, used an illicit drug in 2013. Between these, 1 out of 10 drug users suffers from drug use dependence.</item>
        </list>
      </paragraph>
    </chapter>
